Most common species: Red-breasted nuthatch, black-capped chickadee, house sparrow, house finch
downy woodpecker, white breasted nuthatch, norther cardinal

Notes: windy; Many birds came into view to feed during lulls in the wind

There was snow on the ground from a couple days ago. I am observing from inside, so I can only really hear birds that are close or really loud. I used binoculars to see birds from further away, but that means I may have missed something while I was looking through them. There were some American Crows in the distant trees, but I did not count them because they did not come into my backyard/feeder site
Squirrels were also present in the feeding. There was snow on the ground still

There was snow on the ground, quite icy/hard. Right before I started recording, my dad was outside putting birdseed out. He also put some on our deck during my recording time, so I think some birds were scared off for a little bit.

My dad came back from his walk with our dog part-way through and the sounds from the front yard may have scared some of the birds away from our backyard feeders, because a lot of them left at one point

There is still snow on the ground, but it seems to be melting more now. It was also pretty windy today. There was a squirrel in the feeder site today. There was less seed on the ground and on our deck today, and the snow seemed to cover most of the rest up that was left over from a couple days ago

The snow on the ground has mostly melted, except for some spots closer to the house. There is a new bird feeder in my backyard that is slightly out of my line of vision from the window I have been looking out of for the rest of these session. There were also a lot of squirrels at the site today. My dad came home from walking our dog towards the beginning of this session, so that might have scared some of the birds away from our house.
Multiple feed types - millet, sunflower, peanut, thistle seed
When larger birds were present, smaller birds were less frequent
Lots of pinesiskins today, and where there is one siskin, there are many siskins; low feeders

Most common species: Down Woodpecker, White-breasted Nuthatch, Northern Cardinal
Notes: Very few birds at this time

behavior: Singing for mockingbirds, foraging for everything else
Notes: Typical evening activity in the side yard and adjacent field, lots of foraging birds, a few flybys and the usual heightened activity of the Mockingbirds in the evening. I recorded 5 Mockingbirds, but they are hard to keep track of and I would imagine there were more moving throughout the area.

behavior: Flying for waxwings, foraging for everything else
Notes: It was a bit windier today than yesterday as a storm cloud was moving in off the gulf. This caused the weather to change from sunny to cloudy during the observation time with the wind coming from a SW direction. The first Cedar Waxwing group was an exact count, but the second was an estimate of a 25 bird flock.

behavior: Perching for starlings, foraging for everything else
Notes: Pretty normal evening activity, the Great Egret flyby was the oddball and it was a good evening for warbler species diversity. The local Kestrel is always in the same spot every evening.

behavior: Perching/calling for Blue Jays, foraging for everyting else
Notes: Pretty typical evening, good numbers of Red-bellied, Blue Jay and Mockingbirds. The good old Kestrel has been on its same two perches every evening for the past several months. Pretty neat.
Yard work was going on all week at the neighbor's house, and their dog barks frequently, which may have scared birds away and explain the low count
